description.text:
I wanted a cleaner way to mount my PS4 to my IKEA Jerker desk, so I designed a bracket for that purpose! It's designed to keep the console snug against the desk without being obtrusive. It's over-engineered to be significantly more sturdy than it really needs to be, so don't be afraid to use it for things like wall mounting as well!

I've also uploaded the 123D Design file if anyone wants to remix / improve it!

September 2017 update:

First, thanks everyone who has liked / collected this. It means a lot. I wanted to let you know that this design ALSO works well for a PS4 Pro! It's a little more snug than a standard PS4 because Sony put a bunch of "feet" on the bottom of the Pro, so the one foot in the middle makes this a snug fit on my IKEA Jerker. However it does fit and being a little more snug is probably not a bad thing!

Printed on a Makergear M2 w/ v3b hot end, Black PLA. I went with a 25% infill, but given the reinforcing braces and the general thickness of the piece, you can probably get away with 20% infill and save some plastic and print time. Also you can see from the one photo that you'll want to generate support material for it.

This took almost 9 hours on my M2, so don't start it during a storm!

comments.text:
ABS at 100% infill. Layer heights 0.25-0.3mm. Yea I tried other designs where they suggested lower infills, and I just got frustrated with the fragility of the parts. This month I'm trying out 80 and 90% infills, but I don't expect those to be any tougher than 100%.
3D printed parts do fine for tree branches, tall grass, low to ground tumbling crashes. If I'm flying over 10ft up, clip something, and impact a hard spot on the ground at a steep angle, I'll probably crack an arm.
If the field has cushy grass I typically only break one arm per day. Arm swaps are 15 mins with 1/16 hex, the 3d print wrench, & motor screw wrench. If you crack the chassis plates expect about an hour to replace it.

Hi, I'm a model boat funs come from china, you can call me vcbear,8-)
I have designed a Paddle Boat with 3D printed parts, 3D printing saves me a lot of time on the part production, so , I'd like to share my boat part with all of you.

This is my second prototype because the other ones had some issues when assemble it. Just ask if you have any question!

I got the idea to build a Paddle boat this year for a workshop which organized at “mushroomcloud”. “mushroomcloud” is a well-known makespace in shanghai. china
I used Autodesk 2012 and sketchup8 for the design , my printer was the Overlord from DFRobot, It may took around 2-3 days to print the parts.
The hull is not printed because it would take way too long. So in the first prototype i designed it by Autodesk 2012 ,export to dxf file and get laser cut structure parts.

The boat is driven by two paddle which connected to two TT motors.
The power for the motors comes from a 10000 mAh Lipo Mobile power from xiaomi.
The MCU of the boat is BLUNO, it's a Bluetooth 4.0 Micro-controller Compatible with Arduino Uno, then I plug a 2A Motor Shield for paddle control.
By using the BlueTooth control APP, I can control the boat forword, back, turn left and turn right, it's more Flexible by the two paddle wheels, have fun!!! 8-)

comments.text: Thats incorrect. The ratios on the belt and helix match, the motors are the same, and thus, unless you have a loose belt or bad frame design, you can get just as high of a resolution in X and Y too... The y axis may have more pulleys (2 or 3) but the ratio never changes. If you have a heavy or modified platform (heater / glass), it can screw up the X axis from rebound when dropping or hopping, the X and Y can be reduced by printing too fast (fast = whiplash) or too slow (slow = heat creep, heat warp). You need to learn force equations and know the weight of the carriage (duel machines have to move slightly slower than single, but have much more capability, including dissolvable supports (which is a gigantic step up in quality, and can do multi color prints.), the max torque of the motors when in operation, the ratios of your gears, the thermodynamics in your own nozzle and chamber compared to others like an E3, the material properties, etc, etc.... Basically you need to be an engineer, a scientist, and an artist, to know what your doing. Careful with those ideas, these machines are easy to misinterpret. You need to understand the internal concepts of the machines before someone takes you seriously, something most students dont even learn until their second year. Also, If your 3ds max is coming in sideways, or mesh mixer for that example, its because you havnt configured your settings properly and uniformly on your machine, between software. Its not hard when you get up and make the effort to learn. Yes some mismatch by default, thats why you have settings......

title: z axis depth indicator for QU-BD One Up and Two Up printers

description.text:
Hey there. I came up with this thing to quickly checking the level-ness of my print bed. I actually leave it on the x-axis gantry to check the height before each print. To check the whole bed, I:

lower the hot end to 10mm from plate,
snap on the indicator to check front left and right corner (the spring holder tab serves as a lever for release the clamping pressure)
move the bed forward
check the back left and right corner.
If I leave it on the machine (right side of x-axis) I lose about 30mm in print width when i do that, but it only take 2 seconds to remove it, so it's not a big deal. The depth gage is pretty inexpensive from ebay, and is instant-glued to the print as shown. Hope y'all like it.
p.s.: check your x-axis spacing. This was designed for 55mm ctc.
p.p.s: Some people have asked me if I can put one together for them. The answer is basically yes, but I have a real job, so if you have patience and can wait for a few days, I will be glad to put one together for you. Send me a message.

title: 9V Battery holder with toggle switch mount

description.text: I designed this for a guy at work who needed a mount for a 9VDC battery and a panel mount toggle switch (7mm thru-hole).  It is sized to perfectly fit an energizer battery.   The battery installs upside down to keep all of the wiring to the switch and terminals on the bottom.  In my application it was mounted to a surface on its side.

It turns out there are slight differences in size in 9V batteries.  He was using a Duracell industrial cell that was slightly larger so I printed them scaled up 5% in X and Y.  Printed at 0.2 or 0.3 thickness 2 perimeters, 40% fill.  The retainer snap is printed without support in air.  It could stand to be a bit more aggressive (wider).

This track is designed to fit on standard 1/2" pitch bicycle chain - BMX or similar. The gap between the link holders is designed to allow a standard width skateboard wheel to run in it. Each track link is 24mm long and 100mm wide.

If printing in ABS, keep the bed at 110 degrees C, head temp 240 degrees C, to minimise heat distortion. File is for single item, best to print in a block of 5. The design already includes a raft. Don't specify support structure, it's not needed. I've not tried it in PLA yet!
Degrease bicycle chain, then dismantle it with a link pin remover. Yes, it's time consuming, and you may wear out one or two tools if doing a big track! Put the pins to one side, they aren't needed for this build. You will replace them with M3.5 x 30mm panhead bolts.
For example, if making a chassis approximately 22" long as I am doing, you will need 4 bicycle chains, 100 of these printed links, 400 bolts and 400 nuts, 8 skateboard wheels and 8 sprockets. Printing may take a while, it took me nearly 2 weeks, doing 10 a day, with a few wrecks.
To assemble, put 2 outer chainplates(flat) into recesses inside lugs of printed track part, put a bolt through one of the holes to keep them in place and aligned. Holes may need cleaning out with M3.5 drill to allow bolt to pass freely. Then take 2 inner chainplates(dimpled) and 2 rollers and sandwich the rollers between the plates. The dimples will hold them in place. Hold the outer chainplates apart, non-magnetised tweezers are usefil for this, and slide the inner link into place, it should just fit - secure with a bolt and M3.5 plain nut. You could use M3.5 nylocs, but they cost a fortune for some reason! It's cheaper to just use plain nuts and secure them with a blob of paint on final assembly.

title: Laser Cut Desktop Trebuchet (larger, with wheels and jointed weight basket

description.text:
Design work by Rahul Korpu and Aaron Becker

This enlarged trebuchet has rolling wheels for easy transport, and a jointed weight basket.
This is designed to be cut out of 3/16" plywood that is 1'x1'.

The files were edited in Inkscape, and the original .svg is included: Trebuchet_scaledVx.svg.

A trebuchet (French trébuchet) is a type of catapult that was used as a siege engine in the Middle Ages. It is sometimes called a counterweight trebuchet or counterpoise trebuchet, to distinguish it from an earlier weapon called the traction trebuchet, which employed pulling men working the mechanism.

The counterweight trebuchet appeared in both Christian and Muslim lands around the Mediterranean in the 12th century. It could fling projectiles weighing up to 350 pounds (160 kg) at or into enemy fortifications. Its use continued into the 15th century, well after the introduction of gunpowder. Wikipedia:Trebuchet

This is designed to be cut out of 3/16" plywood that is 1'x1'.
(We purchase 3/16' plywood from Lowe's for $3.48 for a 2'x2' sheet)

  1. print Trebuchet_ScaledVx.pdf to your laser printer
  2. On our 50W C02 VLS3.50, we set
    • black to vector, 100% Power, 90% speed, 500 PPI for etching lines and text
    • red to vector, 100% Power, 8% speed, 500 PPI for cutting interior holes
    • green to vector, 100% Power, 8% speed, 500 PPI for cutting interior holes
  3. trebuchet is assembled using wood glue.

This is a lightweight (approx. 70 grams, depending on printer settings/material), single print, 236mm quadcopter frame.

Your power distribution board and naze32 flight controller can easily be attached with nylon m3 spacers. The esc's and receiver can be attached to the frame with Ty-raps. On the bottom you can fit your battery with straps or Ty-raps.

Specifications:

  • Motor to motor diagonal, 236mm.
  • Motor holes, 16mm/19mm.
  • Prop size, max 5inch.
  • Weight, approx. 70grams, depending on printer settings/material.
  • Flight controller holes, 30.5mm (fits Naze32).
  • Different batteries can be fitted to the bottom with straps or ty-raps.

Products I used:

  • MultiStar & Afro Combo Pack

  • Turnigy 9X 9Ch Transmitter w/ Module & 8ch Receiver (Mode 2)

  • Multistar High Capacity 3S 5200mAh This one is a little bit oversized for this quad, but it carries it easily

  • AfroFlight Naze32 Acro

  • Gemfan 5030

  • I used a custom power distribution board.
Like this design? support me :D

You can set your printer settings as desired to reduce weight or increase strength. No support material is needed. You can try to use the file 'Frame (Reduce warping)' to prevent the arms from warping.

Your power distribution board and naze32 flight controller can easily be attached with nylon m3 spacers. The esc's and receiver can be attached to the frame with Ty-raps. On the bottom you can fit your battery with straps or Ty-raps.

Make sure your props cannot hit any cables by securing them to the frame.

I recently bought a cheap "spy-pen" camera to mount on my HPI Savage-X monster truck to record the action while playing around with it.
There isn't much place to mount the cam and the easiest in my mind is on the front bumper right behind the bull-bar.
The bumper mount provides for adjustment so you can adjust the pen cam's angle to your liking.
Obviously, only the upper half of the pen with the cam is mounted and not the full length pen.

Remove the front upper bumper/bull-bar assembly and remove the dummy spot-lights. Fit the "hpi bumper mount" in place of the spot lights using two M3 bolts and nuts (preferably nylock nuts). The "pen socket" is to be fitted upright "over" the bumper mount with a M3 x 16mm bolt and nut. On the front-inside of the "pen socket" are two recesses for M3 nuts. This might be a little tricky to fit and keep in place. These nuts are for the two M3 x 16mm bolts that hold the "pen socket" over the upper bar of the bull-bar. You might have to use two washers on each bolt to help prevent them from protruding into the pen socket and touching the pen's body. Insert the pen cam and use a M3 bolt and nut at the top of the socket to pinch the socket a bit to secure the pen cam from popping out whn "driving" the monster truck over rough terrain. Adjust the pen cam's angle to your liking and tighten all bolts.

description.text:
This is an acoustic amplifying horn for an iPhone4. In this project I tried to achieve a new level of finishing for 3D print parts, to do this, I incorporated a new technique to glue PLA and normal wallpaper as I describe in instructions.

The idea behind this design is to give a mechanical joining between paper and PLA, because when white glue hardness is trap in little holes in the grid structure, obvious these no chemical joining between PLA and white glue.

I hope this technique will be inspire to others ideas, please share this ideas.

Instructions to do It:

  • You need to print parts with NO top infill/bottom infill, for it I used Cura slice engine to have top infill like a GRID ( I use 25% of infill).
  • After that, put as a top layer the wallpaper piece and glue with NORMAL WHITE GLUE, put glue sufficient to fill the holes in the grid, generous amount of glue.
  • After 48 hours, cut of the excess paper.
  • To finish, you need to join the two parts with a super glue (white glue doesn't work to glue PLA parts).

description.text:
Binary Adding Machine

This is a 3D printable 1/2 scale version of the wooden binary adding machine by Matthias Wandel: http://www.sentex.net/~mwandel/

See a short demo of the 3D printed version here: First time glitched on "32", but second time worked as it usually does: http://youtu.be/GhgaMkGWSNI I may make a better video showing how it adds up a series of numbers, up to 63. The machine resets or wraps around 64.

Educational device to see the binary system in action. Watch as binary bits and bytes toggle in physical form. The steel balls will register the sum of all the values being added together.

Read the article on 3Dprint.com http://3dprint.com/92406/3d-printed-binary-adding/

Based on http://woodgears.ca/marbleadd/
Demonstration of the original wooden model: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GcDshWmhF4A

Designed for 5/16" steel balls.

Got mine at: http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B004PX9KP4/donscollecti

For the Simplify3D users, I uploaded a Base Assembly factory file with custom supports that worked beautifully for me. The trick is to not let any supports get on top of the exit ramp. You can support the overhang at the top well enough by going next to the ramp.

Inventory Build List

  • 1 - Upper Assembly
  • 1 - Base Assembly (Supports are required, see notes)
  • 6 - Rocker Switch
  • 6 - Rocker Post
  • 1 - Input Slider
  • 1 - Upper Number Bar
  • 1 - Result Slider
  • 1 - Return Pool
  • Guard Rails, as needed, the longer drops seem to need them more.

The Upper Number Bar needs to be glued on to hold the Input Slider in the track.

NOTES:

The rocker post is now a separate part because printing them built-on to the upper assembly allowed them to break off too easily. Secondly, this is the one part that people may need to re-size to compensate for printer tolerances and such. Make sure rocker spins freely on the post before installing. I recommend printing two sets of posts and rockers and taking the best combinations from the lot, else you'll be tinkering with trying to get them to spin freely.

Supports on Base Assembly

I used manual supports, which was less that half of what auto gen supports wanted to do. If you can use my Simplify3D factory file, it will trim about an hour off the print job.

Last Minute add ons

Added the guardrail because balls kept jumping out of the columns, then also added a ball collector so I didn't have to chase them or catch them. Lastly, I redesigned the rocker for an unbalanced swept style version so that the OFF side of rocker is heavier. This insures rocker automatically turns off when not being held ON by a ball.
